      "id": "m6qr929r",
      "questionNumber": 6,
      "questionText": "<p>Total number of nucleophiles from the following is :</p><p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m6qtmozq/5a486b39-898d-4514-be2c-0fb513f979f7/f49bfa60-e326-11ef-9ab1-8bface956638/file-jaoe38c1m6qtmozr.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m6qtmozq/5a486b39-898d-4514-be2c-0fb513f979f7/f49bfa60-e326-11ef-9ab1-8bface956638/file-jaoe38c1m6qtmozr.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Main 2025 (Online) 29th January Morning Shift Chemistry - Basics of Organic Chemistry Question 57 English\"></p>",
      "options": [
        "<p>4</p>",
        "<p>6</p>",
        "<p>5</p>",
        "<p>7</p>"
      ],
      "correctOption": 2,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "electron-displacement-effect",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "<p>Nucleophiles are electron rich species and can provide electrons for making new bonds.</p>\n<p>Nucleophiles are nucleus loving species</p>\n<p>* typically have a $-$ve (negative) charge or non-bonding electron pair available for making a new bond.</p>\n<p>Nucleophiles are Lewis bases.</p>\n<p>$\\mathrm{NH}_3$ - It is a nucleophile.</p>\n<p>$\\mathrm{NH}_3$ has a lone pair of electrons on the nitrogen atom which allows it to be a nucleophile since it can provide electrons to form a new bond.</p>\n<p>PhSH - It is a nucleophile</p>\n<p>Lone pair of electrons are present on the sulphone atom and hence it is a nucleophile. The lone pair of electrons are readily donate to form new bonds. with electrophiles.</p>\n<p>$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\mathrm{~S}$ - It is a nucleophile</p>\n<p>The lone pair of electrons on the sulphur atom makes this molecule nucleophile.</p>\n<p>$\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{C}=\\mathrm{CH}_2-$ It is a nuclophile</p>\n<p>Alkenes are nulleophiles because they have a high electron' density in their conbon-conbon double bond. The $\\pi$ bondin $\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CH}_2$ is a region of high election density.</p>\n<p>$$\\mathop O\\limits^\\Theta  H$$ - It is a nucleophile</p>\n<p>Hydroxide ion is a nucleophile, not an electrophile. It is negatively changed and election rich. The electrons are easily donated.</p>\n<p>$\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{\\oplus}$ - It is not a nucleophile</p>\n<p>Hychonium ion is an electrophile. It can gain a pair of electrons from a nucleophile. Also, it is positively changed.</p>\n<p>$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\mathrm{CO}$ - It is not a nucleophile.</p>\n<p>Acetone <img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m82m87bl/85558331-fbb3-4086-8eb6-ee2b9045dc99/a0e62810-fd6f-11ef-9193-210ed46272ab/file-jaoe38c1m82m87bm.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m82m87bl/85558331-fbb3-4086-8eb6-ee2b9045dc99/a0e62810-fd6f-11ef-9193-210ed46272ab/file-jaoe38c1m82m87bm.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Main 2025 (Online) 29th January Morning Shift Chemistry - Basics of Organic Chemistry Question 57 English Explanation 1\"> primarily acts as an electrophile in reactions. It can readily accepts electron pairs from other molecules due to the partial positive charge on the carbonyl carbon atom.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m82m96vd/ac36fc13-7dd7-4bb1-b465-016224764d15/bc5c2f90-fd6f-11ef-9193-210ed46272ab/file-jaoe38c1m82m96ve.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m82m96vd/ac36fc13-7dd7-4bb1-b465-016224764d15/bc5c2f90-fd6f-11ef-9193-210ed46272ab/file-jaoe38c1m82m96ve.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Main 2025 (Online) 29th January Morning Shift Chemistry - Basics of Organic Chemistry Question 57 English Explanation 2\"> - It is not a nucleophile.</p>\n<p>It is an imine compound <img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m82m9sl3/22285a10-fdaf-4b3f-a8b1-4b5c8cdbff99/cd225070-fd6f-11ef-9193-210ed46272ab/file-jaoe38c1m82m9sl4.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m82m9sl3/22285a10-fdaf-4b3f-a8b1-4b5c8cdbff99/cd225070-fd6f-11ef-9193-210ed46272ab/file-jaoe38c1m82m9sl4.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Main 2025 (Online) 29th January Morning Shift Chemistry - Basics of Organic Chemistry Question 57 English Explanation 3\"> and generally act as electrophile in reactions. The carbon in the $C=N$ double bond is electrophile and attacked by nucleophiles.</p>\n<p>So, the nucleophiles are</p>\n<p>$$\\mathrm{NH}_3, \\mathrm{PhSH}, \\quad\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\mathrm{~S}, \\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CH}_2, \\mathrm{OH}^{-}$$</p>\n<p>Total number of nucleophiles is 5</p>",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
